WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.230 --> 00:00:05.640
I'm going to give you over 10 years of
web design knowledge in just 7 minutes.

00:00:05.900 --> 00:00:08.070
No fluff, just the good stuff.

00:00:08.360 --> 00:00:08.969
Are you ready?

00:00:09.270 --> 00:00:09.769
Let's go.

00:00:11.920 --> 00:00:15.099
You can basically boil all the design
knowledge that you need to build great

00:00:15.099 --> 00:00:18.329
websites down to just three things.

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:27.875
websites in somewhat of an F pattern.

00:00:27.885 --> 00:00:31.245
So they start reading at the top
left and then they go right, they

00:00:31.245 --> 00:00:34.045
come back, they go down on the
left, they go right, they come back.

00:00:34.089 --> 00:00:36.620
And they go down on the
left until they're done.

00:00:36.639 --> 00:00:38.150
But here's the truth.

00:00:38.510 --> 00:00:40.380
That's actually bogus.

00:00:40.419 --> 00:00:44.629
It's outdated information that web
designers just kind of keep repeating.

00:00:44.630 --> 00:00:46.550
And so everybody thinks it's true.

00:00:46.579 --> 00:00:48.889
I might have been one
of those web designers.

00:00:48.910 --> 00:00:51.130
And for that, I. Apologize.

00:00:51.180 --> 00:00:56.240
The truth is, is that people engage
with websites and all sorts of different

00:00:56.370 --> 00:01:01.159
patterns and forcing them to pay attention
in an F pattern might actually cause

00:01:01.170 --> 00:01:03.570
them to miss important information.

00:01:03.639 --> 00:01:05.299
So what do you do instead?

00:01:05.609 --> 00:01:08.395
You use something called Visual hierarchy.

00:01:08.405 --> 00:01:12.595
You've probably seen an image before
where there's this big, bold line of

00:01:12.595 --> 00:01:16.675
text that says you're going to read this
first and the smaller line underneath

00:01:16.685 --> 00:01:18.275
it that says, then you'll read it next.

00:01:18.505 --> 00:01:21.364
And then this really tiny line that's
all the way in the left hand corner

00:01:21.364 --> 00:01:23.984
that says, and you'll read this last.

00:01:24.304 --> 00:01:26.014
That is visual hierarchy.

00:01:26.034 --> 00:01:30.304
You make the most important elements of
a section, the biggest and the boldest.

00:01:30.355 --> 00:01:35.704
And then for each other element that isn't
maybe as important, you turn down the

00:01:35.704 --> 00:01:40.584
volume, you make it more inconspicuous
for your call to action or buttons.

00:01:40.594 --> 00:01:43.465
You want to make sure that they
have a high degree of contrast

00:01:43.465 --> 00:01:45.325
from everything else around them.

00:01:45.364 --> 00:01:45.775
Why?

00:01:45.775 --> 00:01:49.564
Because the main thing we want
people to do on a website is click.

00:01:49.659 --> 00:01:50.259
A button.

00:01:50.299 --> 00:01:53.389
If it doesn't stand out, it's
going to make it harder to do that.

00:01:53.420 --> 00:01:57.329
And please, I beg of you,
stop using ghost buttons.

00:01:57.340 --> 00:01:58.479
What are ghost buttons?

00:01:58.530 --> 00:02:02.389
They're buttons that just have an
outline without a solid background.

00:02:02.479 --> 00:02:06.530
The problem is that people don't see
them and they don't click on them.

00:02:06.539 --> 00:02:10.220
For colors, every website should
have a color palette that matches

00:02:10.220 --> 00:02:12.639
the brand of the website owner.

00:02:12.660 --> 00:02:15.900
Here's a few important things to
consider when it comes to color.

00:02:16.180 --> 00:02:18.420
The first thing is accessibility.

00:02:18.570 --> 00:02:23.270
If you pick colors that make it
difficult to read text or tough to

00:02:23.270 --> 00:02:27.590
see elements clearly, it's going
to be hard for users to engage.

00:02:27.610 --> 00:02:31.859
You want to pick colors that have a
high enough contrast that even users

00:02:31.860 --> 00:02:35.839
with visual impairments are still
going to be able to see things clearly.

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:38.530
How do you know if a
contrast is high enough?

00:02:38.550 --> 00:02:41.700
Something that I like using
is a website called coolers.

00:02:41.940 --> 00:02:46.480
co. You can actually take all of
the brand colors from a website.

00:02:46.690 --> 00:02:50.370
Input it into the dashboard, click
on the color contrast teller,

00:02:50.610 --> 00:02:54.710
and it will instantly tell you
which colors pass and which don't.

00:02:54.810 --> 00:02:55.940
Super helpful tool.

00:02:56.040 --> 00:02:59.230
Another good rule of thumb for
colors is that you want to use a

00:02:59.230 --> 00:03:02.480
guideline called the 60 30 10 Rule.

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:05.860
Basically what this means is that
about 60 percent of your website

00:03:05.870 --> 00:03:07.590
should use your dominant colors.

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:12.899
Things like grays or blacks and whites,
30 percent you should reserve for your

00:03:12.910 --> 00:03:18.139
brand colors and then another 10 percent
you want to use something for an accent.

00:03:18.150 --> 00:03:20.430
So helping things really stand out.

00:03:20.470 --> 00:03:25.230
That's a great thing to use for like
your calls to actions or your buttons.

00:03:25.250 --> 00:03:29.270
Is this a hard and fast rule that you
absolutely have to use every single time?

00:03:29.420 --> 00:03:32.360
No, but it's a good principle
to stick with, especially when

00:03:32.360 --> 00:03:33.370
you're first getting started.

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:34.640
Then there's typography.

00:03:34.740 --> 00:03:40.439
Typography is one of the most underrated
design elements of a website, but

00:03:40.439 --> 00:03:43.819
it has a massive impact on the
readability and user experience.

00:03:43.870 --> 00:03:47.149
Thankfully, there's a ton of great
options when it comes to fonts.

00:03:47.149 --> 00:03:51.180
You've got serifs, you've got sans
serifs, you've got handwritten fonts,

00:03:51.180 --> 00:03:52.460
you've got scripts, you've got.

00:03:52.480 --> 00:03:56.790
display, you've got monospace
and it goes on and on.

00:03:56.810 --> 00:03:59.940
There are three main text elements
to consider for your website.

00:03:59.940 --> 00:04:04.169
You've got your H ones or your main
headers, and this should be the biggest,

00:04:04.169 --> 00:04:06.979
most prominent text on the page.

00:04:06.989 --> 00:04:10.280
This is going to describe what
the entire page is all about.

00:04:10.289 --> 00:04:12.800
Then you've got your
H2 or your subheadings.

00:04:12.814 --> 00:04:19.295
These act as ways to divvy up the rest
of the page and guide a user's attention.

00:04:19.324 --> 00:04:22.954
Then finally, you've got your
paragraph text or your P tags.

00:04:22.994 --> 00:04:25.804
You don't want to use really
decorative text for this.

00:04:25.824 --> 00:04:28.804
It might look cool, but
it kills readability.

00:04:28.854 --> 00:04:29.704
But here's the thing.

00:04:29.850 --> 00:04:33.170
Good design without good
conversion practices doesn't

00:04:33.179 --> 00:04:34.850
actually help your clients.

00:04:34.890 --> 00:04:38.530
I designed a website a while back
for a client and the result was

00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:40.980
way better than their old website.

00:04:40.990 --> 00:04:41.689
It was clean.

00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:42.559
It was modern.

00:04:42.559 --> 00:04:44.210
It was chef's kiss.

00:04:44.229 --> 00:04:47.470
The problem was when we
launched it, sales plummeted.

00:04:47.660 --> 00:04:48.769
Why did that happen?

00:04:48.869 --> 00:04:52.760
It's because I tried to make it
look pretty instead of focusing

00:04:52.780 --> 00:04:54.630
on good conversion practices.

00:04:54.670 --> 00:04:57.040
If your design doesn't
consider conversion.

00:04:57.259 --> 00:04:59.040
It's useless to your clients.

00:04:59.050 --> 00:05:01.189
So what are good conversion practices?

00:05:01.220 --> 00:05:04.929
Good conversion is all about
reducing friction for users.

00:05:04.970 --> 00:05:10.759
You want to make it stupid easy for the
users to find what they're looking for and

00:05:10.759 --> 00:05:12.710
to go through and either buy a product.

00:05:12.759 --> 00:05:13.999
or sign up for a service.

00:05:14.040 --> 00:05:15.860
And that's done through clarity.

00:05:15.879 --> 00:05:20.439
You want to be crystal clear about who
the company is or the person is who owns

00:05:20.450 --> 00:05:24.580
the website and what the user is supposed
to do next, why they should even care.

00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:26.710
You also do it through scannability.

00:05:26.759 --> 00:05:30.059
People aren't reading websites,
they're scanning through it.

00:05:30.289 --> 00:05:33.050
So you need to set things out
in such a way that people can

00:05:33.050 --> 00:05:34.929
bounce around and make decisions.

00:05:35.199 --> 00:05:38.190
And then finally, You want
the website to be motivating.

00:05:38.220 --> 00:05:39.930
It's not just enough to be pretty.

00:05:40.090 --> 00:05:43.060
You actually need to speak
to the heart of the user.

00:05:43.060 --> 00:05:47.830
Speak to the thing that's driving them
to say yes or no, but overall, you want

00:05:47.830 --> 00:05:52.760
to design for the right audience, not
for yourself and not for your client.

00:05:52.799 --> 00:05:54.699
It doesn't matter if you love the design.

00:05:54.730 --> 00:05:57.650
It doesn't even matter if
your client loves the design.

00:05:58.140 --> 00:05:59.390
Who does it matter for?

00:05:59.710 --> 00:06:00.940
the website visitors.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:02.240
So do a little research.

00:06:02.290 --> 00:06:04.530
Who's actually using this website?

00:06:04.530 --> 00:06:06.400
Fonts, colors, layout.

00:06:06.670 --> 00:06:10.250
Choose them based on the target
audience and not personal preference.

00:06:10.260 --> 00:06:12.609
Finally, make sure that
you never stop learning.

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:15.140
Web designers don't age
like fine wine, okay?

00:06:15.180 --> 00:06:18.600
We age like a loaf of
bread left on the counter.

00:06:18.760 --> 00:06:21.360
We go stale unless we keep learning.

00:06:21.390 --> 00:06:25.040
The web design industry is changing fast
and it's going to continue to do so.

00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:25.660
What works.

00:06:25.694 --> 00:06:28.244
Just five years ago might not work today.

00:06:28.275 --> 00:06:30.905
It might not work in the next five years.

00:06:30.965 --> 00:06:35.045
And if you don't challenge yourself and
stay updated, you're going to fall behind.

00:06:35.365 --> 00:06:37.814
Will AI take all of our jobs?

00:06:38.704 --> 00:06:39.824
Probably not.

00:06:40.134 --> 00:06:43.334
But will AI take lazy web designer jobs?

00:06:43.795 --> 00:06:44.565
Absolutely.

00:06:44.665 --> 00:06:47.905
The only way to stay valuable
is to keep learning, keep

00:06:47.905 --> 00:06:49.895
adjusting, and keep leveling up.

00:06:49.965 --> 00:06:53.325
And you might be asking yourself, that's
all well and good, but what do I need

00:06:53.325 --> 00:06:55.765
to do if I'm getting started today?

00:06:55.845 --> 00:06:58.744
Thankfully, I've got another video
that I'm going to link to that's

00:06:58.744 --> 00:07:01.175
going to answer just those questions.

00:07:01.425 --> 00:07:04.745
Make sure that you like this video if
it was helpful and be sure to subscribe

00:07:04.745 --> 00:07:06.745
so that you don't miss another episode.

00:07:06.775 --> 00:07:09.695
And don't forget, if
you don't quit, you win.

